<div id="review_951733189" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/951733189" />
    <a title="Laurie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5855886-laurie"><img alt="Laurie" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/951733189?book_show_action=true">May 29, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laurie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laurie" href="/user/show/5855886-laurie">Laurie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer951733189&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer951733189" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11289010884028020617">Much to my surprise this book actually ended up being my favorite in the series thus far. The reason I&apos;m so surprised is it started off very slow. In fact, I was probably 2/3 of the way through before I really got into it, but once it took off, it took off! I loved the theme of re-connecting with one&apos;s cultural roots: &quot;Go back to the beginning.&quot; For Merlin this meant reclaiming the Bard and for Arthur the Warrior-King. There was a sense of the character&apos;s embracing their own archtypes. I also en</span>
  <span id="freeText11289010884028020617" style="display:none">Much to my surprise this book actually ended up being my favorite in the series thus far. The reason I'm so surprised is it started off very slow. In fact, I was probably 2/3 of the way through before I really got into it, but once it took off, it took off! I loved the theme of re-connecting with one's cultural roots: "Go back to the beginning." For Merlin this meant reclaiming the Bard and for Arthur the Warrior-King. There was a sense of the character's embracing their own archtypes. I also enjoyed the re-introduction of the supernatural elements and a break from all the warring. While war is the subject of many an epic, I started to feel bogged down with it, particularly as that was the main motif for the previous book "Arthur." The more personalized combat that ended up crowning this story was far more interesting, and it gave us a sense of Arthur, not just as a war-leader, but as a warrior. Over all, I felt like this book re-booted the series, and I'm excited to see what comes next in "Grail." And of course, I can't leave off a review without rating the series. So far, from most to least favorite: Pendragon, Taliesin, Arthur, Merlin. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11289010884028020617" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


