<span id="freeTextContainer3168296408455738701">It&apos;s a slow slog through this book until the nail-biting end, but it&apos;s an important piece of this author&apos;s Arthurian legend. <br/><br/>There is a /lot/ of war in this book. More and more and more. I wanted more of Arthur as king. But I suppose he has to win his kingdom first. <br/><br/>For a book called Pendragon, it sure focused a lion&apos;s share on Merlin. But that&apos;s ok. Because more Merlin means more Charis. <br/><br/>I love this series, though not as much as I did the first time I read it. </span>
  <span id="freeText3168296408455738701" style="display:none">It's a slow slog through this book until the nail-biting end, but it's an important piece of this author's Arthurian legend. <br /><br />There is a /lot/ of war in this book. More and more and more. I wanted more of Arthur as king. But I suppose he has to win his kingdom first. <br /><br />For a book called Pendragon, it sure focused a lion's share on Merlin. But that's ok. Because more Merlin means more Charis. <br /><br />I love this series, though not as much as I did the first time I read it. </span>
